---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '@/components/Header.astro';

const title = "Cost-aware cascades beat LLM-judges by a factor of ~1,000×";
const date = '2026-05-12';
const description =
  "A cheap rule layer plus an XGBoost classifier handles 99.9% of the load. The LLM judge only gets the ambiguous 0.1%, and that's what makes the bill fit on a page.";
---

<Layout title={`${title} — Aojie Yuan`} description={description}>
  <main>
    <Header current="writing" />

    <article>
      <header class="post-head">
        <a href="/writing" class="back">← Writing</a>
        <time datetime={date}>
          {new Date(date).toLocaleDateString('en-US', { year: 'numeric', month: 'long', day: 'numeric' })}
        </time>
        <h1>{title}</h1>
        <p class="lede">{description}</p>
      </header>

      <section class="prose">
        <p>
          Building AEGIS, the obvious naïve baseline for "is this tool call
          safe?" is to hand every call to an LLM judge — Claude or GPT — and
          let it think. The judges work. On our benchmark they hit 96.6%
          block rate. They also add 1–4 seconds of latency per call and cost
          between $0.36 and $5.32 per run, depending on the model. Multiply
          by the number of tool calls in a real agent session and the
          unit economics fall apart before you can ship a free tier.
        </p>

        <p>
          The alternative most teams try is hand-written rules. They're fast
          (well under a millisecond), free, and they miss everything you
          didn't think of in advance. On the same benchmark, our pure rule
          layer blocks 0% of the out-of-distribution attacks.
        </p>

        <p>
          We ended up at the obvious-in-retrospect middle: a <em>cascade</em>.
        </p>

        <h2>The shape of the thing</h2>

        <p>
          Three layers, each cheaper than the last is allowed to be:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>L1 — Rules.</strong> Pattern matching on tool name and
            arguments. Sub-millisecond. Catches the clear-cut cases
            (<code>DROP TABLE</code>, <code>rm -rf /</code>,
            <code>npm publish</code>, known prompt-injection templates).
            High recall on the obvious, zero recall on anything novel.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>L2 — XGBoost over structured features.</strong> Fifteen
            features derived from the tool call: argument shape, length
            ratios, suspicious-token ratios, classifier output. Trained
            supervised on labeled malicious/benign data. About 50&nbsp;ms.
            This is where the recall comes from on attacks the rules never
            saw.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>L3 — LLM judge.</strong> Only fires when L2's confidence
            sits in a configured ambiguity band (between, say, 0.4 and 0.7).
            Adds the latency and cost, but only for the few percent of
            calls that need it.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>The number that matters</h2>

        <p>
          On a 5,525-call benchmark stitched together from four public
          sources, the full cascade hits <strong>99.9% block rate at 1.1&nbsp;ms
          p50 latency and $0.05 per run</strong>. The LLM judges on their own:
          96.6% block at 1–4&nbsp;s and $0.36–$5.32. Pure rules: 0% block on
          out-of-distribution, near-zero cost.
        </p>

        <p>
          The cascade isn't strictly better than the LLM-only baseline on
          recall (we still miss a small slice that judges catch with deep
          reasoning), but it wins on every other axis simultaneously —
          latency, cost, and explainability. For a production firewall, that
          asymmetry matters more than the last fraction of a percent.
        </p>

        <h2>What's actually doing the work</h2>

        <p>
          The temptation in this kind of design is to spend all your
          attention on L2 — the ML model is the interesting part. In
          practice, the ratios mostly come from <em>how often each layer
          fires</em>. On our benchmark, L1 finalizes about 70% of calls
          (allow or block). L2 finalizes another ~28%. The expensive judge
          gets the remaining ~2%. If you tune that ratio wrong — say, L2
          confident only on 50% — your cost goes up 25×. The thresholds
          aren't a knob, they're <em>the</em> knob.
        </p>

        <h2>The thing nobody writes about</h2>

        <p>
          The L1 layer doesn't just save money — it makes the system <em>auditable</em>.
          When a call is blocked by a regex on the SQL argument, the reason
          is a string a customer can read. When it's blocked by an LLM
          judge, the reason is a paragraph that often disagrees with the
          paragraph it produced last week on the same input. For a
          security product whose customers will face SOC&nbsp;2 evidence
          requests, deterministic-cheap-explainable beats statistical-
          expensive-vibes every time.
        </p>

        <p>
          The cascade isn't a clever trick. It's the obvious shape once you
          take cost and explainability as first-class as recall. We spent
          longer than I'd like to admit assuming the "right" answer was a
          fancier classifier.
        </p>
      </section>
    </article>
  </main>

  <style>
    main {
      max-width: 640px;
      margin: 0 auto;
      padding: 1.5rem 1.75rem 6rem;
    }
    .post-head {
      margin: 4rem 0 3rem;
    }
    .back {
      font-size: 0.85rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      border-bottom-color: transparent;
      display: inline-block;
      margin-bottom: 2rem;
    }
    .back:hover {
      color: var(--text);
      border-bottom-color: var(--text);
    }
    .post-head time {
      font-size: 0.78rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      letter-spacing: 0.05em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      display: block;
      margin-bottom: 0.7rem;
    }
    h1 {
      font-size: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 3rem);
      line-height: 1.15;
      margin: 0 0 1.2rem;
      letter-spacing: -0.014em;
    }
    .lede {
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      max-width: 46ch;
      line-height: 1.55;
      margin: 0;
    }
    .prose {
      font-size: 1.04rem;
      line-height: 1.72;
    }
    .prose h2 {
      font-size: 1.55rem;
      margin: 3rem 0 1rem;
      line-height: 1.3;
    }
    .prose p {
      margin: 0 0 1.3rem;
    }
    .prose ul {
      padding-left: 1.3rem;
      margin: 0 0 1.5rem;
    }
    .prose li {
      margin-bottom: 0.7rem;
    }
    .prose code {
      background: var(--surface);
      padding: 0.1rem 0.4rem;
      border-radius: 3px;
      font-size: 0.86em;
      border: 1px solid var(--hairline);
    }
    .prose em {
      font-style: italic;
      color: var(--accent);
    }
    .prose strong {
      font-weight: 600;
      color: var(--text);
    }
  </style>
</Layout>
